# UDS Figma Component Card — Update Mode

Companion to [`uds-figma-component-card.mdc`](./uds-figma-component-card.mdc). The
card rule defines the canonical seven-section layout (HEADER → ANATOMY →
VARIANTS → SUB-COMPONENTS → USAGE → ACCESSIBILITY → META) for every component
page in the UDS Components Figma file. **This rule defines what to do when a
card already exists on a page** — i.e., when the builder is being re-run for a
rollout, a re-apply, an "is the card up to date?" check, or any repeat
invocation that would otherwise tear down good work.

## Why this rule exists

Earlier rollouts treated every run as a blind rebuild. That worked for the
pilot, but as cards age:

- The `📐 _TEMPLATE` page evolves (new field, new section, restructured
  eyebrow, new token bindings).
- The page accumulates new content (additional component sets, more state
  variants, new sub-components) that the prior card layout doesn't know about.
- The component's `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json` gets richer
  (description rewrites, owner changes, new keyboard rows, additional
  `whenToUse` text).

A blind rebuild would either lose newly added page content or re-stamp a stale
card. Update mode prevents both.

## When to use this rule

Default behavior for **any** repeat invocation of the card builder:

- "Roll out the component card design across the library"
- "Re-apply the card design to every in-progress component"
- "Check if the cards are up to date"
- "Update the figma page for X" when X already has a `udc-<id>-page` frame
- Any second-or-later run of the [`figma-component-card`](../skills/figma-component-card/SKILL.md) skill on a given component

The first time a card is built on a page, the original card rule applies
(create mode). After that, this rule supplements it.

## Decision tree (per page)

For each component page in scope:

1. **Inventory the page.** Walk every top-level node AND every descendant of
   any existing `udc-<id>-page` frame. Capture every `COMPONENT`,
   `COMPONENT_SET`, and `INSTANCE` so nothing can be lost.
2. **Look for an existing card.** Find the top-level frame named
   `udc-<id>-page`.
3. **Decide:**

   | Condition | Action |
   |---|---|
   | No `udc-<id>-page` frame exists | **Create mode** — run the full builder per the original card rule |
   | Frame exists, matches current `📐 _TEMPLATE`, no new page content to absorb, all spec.json fields in sync | **No-op** — emit a write summary that says "no-op — already in sync"; do nothing else |
   | Frame exists, ANY drift (template, page content, or spec.json) | **Update mode** — see below |

## Three diff sources for drift detection

A card is considered out of date if ANY of the following diverges from what
the card currently shows:

1. **Template diff** — compare the existing card's structure against the
   current `📐 _TEMPLATE` page in the same Figma file. Look for: new
   sections, removed sections, changed eyebrow text, new token bindings,
   restructured rows, added/removed pills, etc. The template is the visual
   source of truth (the card rule says so); if the template moved, the card
   needs to follow.
2. **Page-content diff** — compare the COMPONENTs, COMPONENT_SETs, and
   INSTANCEs the page contains (top-level + everything nested inside the
   existing `udc-<id>-page`) against what's actually represented inside the
   card sections. New component sets that aren't yet placed in VARIANTS, new
   underscored sub-components that aren't in SUB-COMPONENTS, additional state
   variants of the primary set that aren't in ANATOMY — all signal drift.
3. **Spec.json diff** — compare the card's text content against the current
   `uds-docs/uds/components/<id>/spec.json` and `status.json`. Fields to
   check: `title`, `description`, `whenToUse`, `whenNotToUse`,
   `accessibility.keyboard[]`, `owner.designer`, `owner.developer`,
   `dependencies.css[0]`, status pill label/colors. If any of those moved,
   the card text is stale.

If any of the three diffs reports a difference, run update mode. If all three
match, the card is up-to-date and the builder no-ops.

## Update mode — the no-content-loss guarantee

Update mode is reasonably implemented as **"tear down the existing card
frame, but only after inventorying every COMPONENT / COMPONENT_SET /
INSTANCE it contains, then feed those node IDs into the builder's
reparenting logic so nothing is lost."** Concretely:

1. **Inventory before destroying.** The builder MUST walk the existing
   `udc-<id>-page` frame's full descendant tree and collect every
   `COMPONENT_SET` and `COMPONENT` (and any `INSTANCE` that should survive)
   into a flat list of node IDs. Do this BEFORE moving any nodes or
   removing any frames.
2. **Park the inventoried nodes.** Reparent them to a temp position at page
   level (e.g. `(5000, -5000)`) so they're not destroyed when the wrapper
   is removed. `appendChild` preserves node identity, so library bindings,
   variant references, and Code Connect mappings all survive.
3. **Tear down the wrapper.** Only after every inventoried node is parked.
4. **Rebuild the wrapper from scratch** using the latest template + spec
   content.
5. **Reparent the parked nodes back into the new card.** Place them in
   the appropriate section (primary set → ANATOMY hero / first VARIANTS
   slot, additional sets → VARIANTS, underscored sets → SUB-COMPONENTS).
6. **Verify zero loss.** Compare the post-rebuild inventory against the
   pre-teardown inventory. Every node in the pre-teardown list must be
   accounted for inside the new card. If anything ended up in the builder's
   `droppedNodes` return field, **STOP and report** — do not continue with
   more components. Content loss is a critical failure, not a warning.
7. **Verify zero duplication.** No COMPONENT_SET or COMPONENT ID should
   appear twice on the page. If the inventory pass picked up a node both
   from the page top level AND from inside the old wrapper (for example,
   because a previous half-finished run left a copy), that's an error
   condition — STOP and report rather than guessing which copy is canonical.

## Per-component reporting

Every update-mode run MUST emit the standard Figma write summary block from
[`uds-figma-write-safety.mdc`](./uds-figma-write-safety.mdc), with the
operation field set to `update` (not `create` or `rebuild`):

```markdown
## Figma write summary

- File: UDS Components | UDS Components Testbed
- File key: ...
- Page: <emoji + component-id>
- Node/frame: udc-<id>-page (root frame), plus content + 7 section cards
- Operation: update
- Old value: <brief structural description of the prior card; cite the drift source(s) — template, page-content, spec.json>
- New value: <new wrapper dimensions and section list>
- Component sets reparented: <list of IDs and their new parent cards>
- Component sets duplicated/deleted: <should be empty — flag if not>
- Inventory delta: <added / preserved / dropped counts>
- Rollback note: existing component sets are reparented in place; revert by re-parenting back to page level and deleting the udc-<id>-page wrapper
```

For no-op runs, emit a write summary anyway with operation `no-op` and a one-line reason (e.g. "no template, page-content, or spec.json drift detected").

## Interaction with the original card rule

This rule **supplements** [`uds-figma-component-card.mdc`](./uds-figma-component-card.mdc),
it does not replace it. Card structure, token bindings, eyebrow recipes, link
cards, status colors, "don't renumber eyebrows" — all of that is governed by
the original card rule. This rule only governs **whether to rebuild** and
**how to preserve content during a rebuild**. When in doubt about layout or
binding details, defer to the card rule.

The skill ([`figma-component-card`](../skills/figma-component-card/SKILL.md))
must call out update mode as the default behavior for any page that already
has a `udc-<id>-page` frame, and must reference both rules.

## What still applies

- **Read-only on `uds-docs/uds/`** — see
  [`uds-source-of-truth.mdc`](./uds-source-of-truth.mdc). Update mode reads
  spec.json/status.json to detect drift, never writes them.
- **Figma write safety** — every update-mode run is a Figma write and must
  follow [`uds-figma-write-safety.mdc`](./uds-figma-write-safety.mdc),
  including the standard write summary.
- **Pre-flight first** — see
  [`uds-figma-preflight.mdc`](./uds-figma-preflight.mdc). Inventory and diff
  are read-only operations; they happen before any teardown.
- **Status mismatch is not this rule's job** — if the Figma page-name
  stoplight prefix disagrees with `status.json#current`, STOP and surface
  it; that's a [`sync-figma-component-status`](../skills/sync-figma-component-status/SKILL.md) job.
- **Library subscription** — `UDS Tokens` must be subscribed before any
  rebuild, same as create mode.

